    "id": 285,
    "text": "Finishing practice.\n\nMost sessions: Line of players. Ball fed in. Shot at goal.\n\nThis teaches nothing about game finishing.\n\nHere's what works:\n\n---\n\nGame finishing involves:\n\n- Movement before the ball\n- Receiving under pressure\n- Quick decision-making\n- Different angles and distances\n\nYour drills need all of this.\n\n---\n\nStart with types of finish.\n\nInside foot (placement)\nInstep (power)\nChip (over keeper)\nOne-touch (speed)\n\nTeach the tool, then the application.\n\n---\n\nAdd decision-making.\n\nTwo goals. Keeper moves. Player chooses.\n\nOne touch. Two touch. Depends on time.\n\nThe drill should require decisions.\n\n---\n\nMake it realistic.\n\nBall arrives from different angles.\nDefender applies pressure.\nTime is limited.\n\nNo more perfect balls to nowhere.\n\n---\n\nRepetition with quality.\n\nFinishing needs lots of attempts.\n\nBut 50 bad shots doesn't beat 20 quality ones.\n\nSet up for success, then add challenge.\n\n---\n\n8 finishing exercises from basic to game-realistic are in the classroom.\n\nProgressive complexity. Clear coaching points.\n\nInside the Football Coaching Academy. Link in bio."
