    "text": "\"The talented kids with a bad attitude are the absolute worst. So difficult to deal with.\"\n\nEvery coach has been there.\n\nHere's what I've learned about handling this:\n\n---\n\nFirst, understand where it comes from.\n\nOften it's:\n- Fear of failure masked as arrogance\n- Frustration with teammates\n- Pressure from parents\n- Being praised for talent, not effort\n\nThe attitude is a symptom. Not the problem.\n\n---\n\nSeparate the behaviour from the player.\n\n\"That reaction wasn't acceptable\" is different from \"You're a problem.\"\n\nOne addresses the action. The other labels the person.\n\nKids live up (or down) to labels.\n\n---\n\nSet clear standards for everyone.\n\nNo special treatment because they're talented.\n\nIf the rule is \"we encourage teammates,\" it applies to your best player too.\n\nConsistency builds culture.\n\n---\n\nGive them responsibility.\n\n\"I need you to help the team when we're struggling.\"\n\nChannel the energy. Make their attitude a leadership opportunity.\n\nSome kids don't know how to lead positively. Show them.\n\n---\n\nSometimes you have to make hard choices.\n\nA bad attitude will rub off on other kids and cause more issues.\n\nOne player's talent isn't worth destroying your team culture.\n\n---\n\n\"I will always take someone who has a great attitude and tries hard, regardless of talent.\"\n\nThis is the way.\n\nMore coaching wisdom from 1,500+ coaches who get it. Free community. Link in bio."
