    "text": "\"I coach a 9v9 squad solo and started the season with 14 players. That was difficult.\"\n\nSound familiar?\n\nHere's how to survive (and thrive) coaching alone:\n\n---\n\nStructure is your assistant coach.\n\nSet up activities that run themselves.\n\nRondos. Possession grids. SSGs with clear rules.\n\nThe less you need to intervene, the more you can observe and coach.\n\n---\n\nCreate player leaders.\n\nPick 2-3 players to help with:\n- Equipment setup\n- Timing activities\n- Demonstrating exercises\n\nThey learn leadership. You get breathing room.\n\n---\n\nUse \"waves\" for drills.\n\nInstead of 14 players in one activity, run two groups alternating.\n\nGroup A works. Group B recovers.\n\nSmaller groups = more touches = better development.\n\n---\n\nSimplify your session structure.\n\nWarm-up (10 min)\nTechnical (15 min)\nSSG (25 min)\n\nThree activities. That's it.\n\nComplexity doesn't mean quality.\n\n---\n\nAccept what you can't control.\n\nYou won't give individual feedback to every player every session.\n\nBut you can create an environment where they all get better together.\n\n---\n\nSolo coaching is hard. But it doesn't have to be lonely.\n\nJoin 1,500+ coaches sharing what actually works.\n\nSessions, support, solutions. Free community. Link in bio."
